\noindent 1.3.4:

\noindent (1) Let $K$ be the statement "you will kiss me," and let
$J$ be the statement "I will dance a jig."  The question is whether
$(K\rightarrow J)\wedge J$ implies $K$, which it does not.  You can
verify it doesn't using a truth table. The failing case is when $K$
is false, and $J$ is true.  Thus $(K\rightarrow J)\wedge J$ is true
while $K$ is false.

\vspace{0.25cm}

\noindent (3) Let $P$ be the statement "cars pollute" and $T$ be the
statement "we are in trouble."  $(P\rightarrow T)\wedge P
\Rightarrow T$ by modus ponens.

\vspace{0.25cm}

\noindent (4) Let $T$ be the statement "our time is short," $E$ be
the statement "the end is near," and $D$ be the statement "doom is
impending."  The question is whether $(T\vee E)\wedge D$ implies
$E$, which it does not.  Take the case where $T$ is true, $E$ is
false, and $D$ is true.  Thus, $(T\vee E)\wedge D$ is true, but $E$
is false.

\vspace{0.5cm}

