\noindent 1.3.5:

\noindent (2) Let $S$ be the statement "this shirt has stripes," $L$
be the statement "this shirt has short sleeves," and $B$ be the
statement "this shirt has a band collar."  Thus the statements in
question are $S\wedge(L\vee B)$ and $(S\wedge L)\vee B$ which are
not equivalent.  Take the case when $L$ and $B$ are true but $S$ is
false.  Thus $S\wedge(L\vee B)$ is false while $(S\wedge L)\vee B$
is true.

\vspace{0.25cm}

\noindent (5) Let $R$ be the statement "melons are ripe," and $S$ be
the statement "melons are soft to the touch." $\neg(R\leftrightarrow
S)$ is not equivalent to $(R\wedge S)\vee (\neg R \vee  \neg S)$.
Take the case where $R$ and $S$ are true.  Thus
$\neg(R\leftrightarrow S)$ is false, while $(R\wedge S)\vee (\neg R
\vee  \neg S)$ is true.  The second statement is a tautology, while
the first is not.

